Dev Log - 2026-05-10

Summary

contract hardening day

Today was mainly about turning the automated worker-control slice from a broad idea into something with clearer boundaries and better runtime truth. The work centered on the Command Center, its recommendation-only orchestration path, and the supporting contracts around leases, validation, and commit gating. The important part is not that more UI or more automation appeared, but that the system became more explicit about what it can and cannot do.

The day also had a second thread: tightening the proof trail. Several changes were made specifically to rerun live evidence after null-safety and render-path repairs, which made the supported path more trustworthy without pretending the unsupported paths were solved.

What I completed

Command Center worker control plane

- Added the Command Center worker control panel and the backend work-order/task-board API.
- Added orchestrator next-task recommendation selection so the UI can inspect what is eligible without dispatching work.
- Clarified the decentralized network operating model in the release/docs layer so the new worker-control surface stays aligned with the project’s boundary language.
- Refreshed the weekly current-state override to keep the short-horizon truth in sync with the new operator surfaces.

What changed here:
- The Command Center now has a visible control surface for work-order inspection, create/cancel, and recommendation-only next-task review.
- The orchestration path is more explicit about being non-dispatch.
- The current-state docs now say that plainly, which matters because the system is easy to overclaim if the docs lag the code.

Worker control proof and repair

- Added the initial live proof for the worker control plane.
- Repaired the Command Center worker control panel render path.
- Reran the live proof after the render repair.
- Repaired Command Center observability null safety.
- Reran the live proof again after the null-safety repair.
- Reran the coding-result return-path proof after the packaging fix.

What changed here:
- The Command Center stopped failing immediately on the observability/render seam and became stable enough to re-exercise under live conditions.
- The proof artifacts now show the difference between a surface that loads and a surface that is actually stable under observability reads.
- The coding-result path is still not something I would describe as fully release-proven from this evidence alone; the rerun exists, but the supporting truth still needs care.

Worker contract hardening

- Made the coding worker honor worktree leases.
- Added the commit-after-green gate.
- Added bounded validation retry attempts and the single-attempt validation command path.
- Added mutation-scope guardrails and related token fixes.
- Reconciled boundary conflicts in the coding-worker control flow.

What changed here:
- The worker now behaves more like a governed process and less like an open-ended executor.
- Validation, commit, and lease behavior are now separated enough to reason about failure modes instead of assuming success.
- The protocol-token cleanup matters because these control paths are only as honest as their shared constants.

Campaign/spec alignment

- Mapped the Symphony spec to the worker control plane.
- Added the adaptation matrix for that mapping.

What changed here:
- The campaign/spec layer now has a concrete bridge to the worker-control implementation.
- That helps keep the spec from drifting into aspirational language that the runtime cannot actually satisfy.

Persona Studio and UI contracts

- Refined Persona Studio persistence and layout contracts.
- Tightened chat and sidebar shell behavior through the broader day’s related work.

What changed here:
- The shell work is less likely to collapse into ambiguous or brittle state.
- This was not flashy UI work; it was structural cleanup so the surfaces keep their shape under real use.

Important outcome

The biggest shift is that the worker-control system now has a real boundary instead of a blurred promise. Command Center is no longer just a placeholder for “someday orchestration”; it now exposes a recommendation-only control plane with create/list/detail/cancel behavior and live proof artifacts behind it.

Just as important, the system stopped pretending dispatch was part of the supported story. The current-state docs now match that boundary: visibility and recommendation are real, dispatch is not. That is a much safer place to build from than a UI that implies more automation than the runtime can actually deliver.

