Narrative Log

Dev Log - 2026-05-10

It was a boundary day. Not a feature-sprint day in the shallow sense, but a day spent making the worker-control system more legible, more bounded, and harder to misread.

The main arc ran through Command Center. First came the control panel itself, then the backend task-board API and orchestrator recommendation selector, and then the live proof work that tried to break the seam in realistic conditions. That sequence mattered. It turned the UI from a static shell into a surface that can show work orders, recommendations, and cancellations without pretending to dispatch anything. The proof artifacts are important because they mark the difference between “this renders” and “this holds up under the supported path.”

Then the runtime made its own corrections. The worker-control panel had a render-path issue, and observability itself introduced a null-safety problem. Both were repaired, and both were worth treating as first-class work because they exposed the same underlying lesson: once a control surface starts reading real runtime state, it has to survive the shape of that state. After those repairs, the live proof could be rerun, which made the seam materially more trustworthy.

The backend side got its own discipline. Worktree leases, commit-after-green gating, bounded validation attempts, mutation scoping, and token cleanup all pushed the coding worker toward something governed rather than improvisational. That is not glamorous work, but it is the kind that prevents a control loop from turning into a pile of side effects. The system is better when it knows what it owns, what it can touch, and when it must stop.

There was also a slower-docs thread running underneath everything. The current-state override and the decentralized operating model language were refreshed so the repo’s short-horizon truth stayed aligned with what the code now does. That alignment matters more than it sounds like it should. A system like this gets dangerous when the docs start implying dispatch, federation, or release readiness before the runtime has actually earned those claims.

The deeper change today was not just that the worker-control plane exists. It is that it now has an honest shape: recommendation-only, non-dispatch, visible, and more stable under its own observability. That makes the next slice possible without smuggling in assumptions the system has not proven yet.

The next useful move is to keep pressure on the remaining runtime seams, especially the coding-result return path, while preserving the boundary discipline that made today’s work meaningful.


